1
00:00:00,993 --> 00:00:27,725
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:29,292 --> 00:00:39,194
Homage to the blessed, noble, and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:39,856 --> 00:00:43,182
This is going to try and talk about Vedana, feeling.

4
00:00:44,479 --> 00:00:54,871
I'm going to try and make a distinction between what are known as the Mahabhuta, the four elements, and the Sankara, which we would translate as mental, emotional states.

5
00:00:56,512 --> 00:01:12,310
I'm going to see where it fits into the schema of the wheel of dependent origination, and then try and understand the way the Buddha actually wanted us to experience these through the discourse on how to establish mindfulness and become enlightened very quickly.

6
00:01:15,141 --> 00:01:36,254
One thing that I think we all suffer from is a sort of confusion, perhaps that's too strong a word, between the way that the West understands psychology and the way the Buddha understood it.

7
00:01:37,989 --> 00:01:53,936
Just in my own little life story, there was a time when I read a lot about this stuff, Western psychology, and I came to the conclusion that I had truly sorted myself out.

8
00:01:55,237 --> 00:01:58,343
Only to find in a couple of years myself in this pit.

9
00:01:59,926 --> 00:02:01,347
And when I got into this pit...

10
00:02:02,441 --> 00:02:06,009
The only thing that came to mind was to do Zen meditation.

11
00:02:06,028 --> 00:02:07,131
I don't have a clue why.

12
00:02:07,671 --> 00:02:10,195
I mean it was in the air and I'd read a book and all that.

13
00:02:11,799 --> 00:02:16,367
So I wrote to the Buddhist Society and said I need to go to Japan to do meditation.

14
00:02:16,829 --> 00:02:20,855
And they wrote back with a letter with 21 points as to why I shouldn't go.

15
00:02:22,169 --> 00:02:39,245
So I gave that up, and I ended up in a very exotic town of Birmingham and started practicing Zen according to the tradition of Throstle Hole Abbey, which some of you may know up in Northumberland.

16
00:02:39,504 --> 00:02:42,268
And I was still doing a little bit of my own therapy.

17
00:02:42,587 --> 00:02:44,550
I think I beat the hell out of this mattress.

18
00:02:46,012 --> 00:02:48,514
And I found that that got me so far

19
00:02:49,793 --> 00:02:51,373
I've got rid of this whole surface stuff.

20
00:02:52,074 --> 00:02:56,459
But then the more I got into meditation, the more I found a way of dealing with it.

21
00:02:57,580 --> 00:03:08,750
And I was lucky in this sense that by the time I came to meditation, I'd actually given up hope, both on the Christian path and psychotherapy and all that.

22
00:03:09,230 --> 00:03:16,456
So when I entered Zen, and they just told me to sit and watch, just sit and observe, I took it at face value.

23
00:03:16,896 --> 00:03:19,800
I don't remember asking any questions as to why.

24
00:03:19,983 --> 00:03:24,044
And Zen, of course, doesn't offer you many answers for it.

25
00:03:24,486 --> 00:03:26,296
Just presumes you'll discover why.

26
00:03:28,487 --> 00:03:48,939
But it was only when I came to Theravada Buddhism with its sort of psychological basis, the way that it goes to great lengths to describe how and why we end up in certain places, that things began to fall into place for me intellectually.

27
00:03:49,441 --> 00:03:56,352
I began to understand what had been happening to me, especially through Zen and later through this meditation.

28
00:03:56,331 --> 00:04:05,182
And again, when I went to practice with these Eastern teachers, you weren't given any reasons.

29
00:04:05,562 --> 00:04:10,169
You were just told to watch the breath and whatever comes up.

30
00:04:10,188 --> 00:04:17,276
And if you asked a question, they sort of looked at you, sort of mystified, wondering why the hell you wanted to know anyway.

31
00:04:17,999 --> 00:04:20,603
It's a strange thing to have to go through.

32
00:04:21,745 --> 00:04:26,250
And normally the reply was just something like, watch the breath.

33
00:04:29,896 --> 00:04:35,485
Slowly, through the experience of meditation, of course, these things do become clear.

34
00:04:36,375 --> 00:04:49,434
And what became very clear to me as I began to progress was that unless you actually see what you're doing through the eyes of the Buddha, you can waste a lot of time.

35
00:04:50,735 --> 00:04:51,637
Waste a lot of time.

36
00:04:52,458 --> 00:04:58,446
And waste a lot of time trying to psychoanalyze yourself or psychotherapeutize yourself.

37
00:04:58,505 --> 00:05:00,548
It's a sort of wrong view.

38
00:05:00,588 --> 00:05:02,411
And we get caught up in it.

39
00:05:02,432 --> 00:05:04,915
It's very easy because it's just part of our culture.

40
00:05:05,569 --> 00:05:24,649
But when you actually position yourself right and you get this way of looking at it, the way the Buddha asked us to, then you'll see there's a clarity comes about as to what the practice is doing, both at the psychotherapeutic level and at that deeper level of spirituality.

41
00:05:26,831 --> 00:05:34,699
So the first thing I would like to explain is the way the Buddha explained how we experience things, how we come to know something.

42
00:05:37,766 --> 00:05:51,461
In terms of the first contact that we have with the outside world, he actually called it contact, translates the word pasta for those of you who know.

43
00:05:51,480 --> 00:05:59,930
And this contact produces in the body a very simple sensation, extraordinarily simple sensation.

44
00:06:01,851 --> 00:06:06,677
At the eardrum, it's simply the tapping of the airwave on the eardrum.

45
00:06:07,281 --> 00:06:09,204
There's no sound to it at all.

46
00:06:09,425 --> 00:06:11,146
That's how basic it is.

47
00:06:12,709 --> 00:06:14,031
And the eye, what is it?

48
00:06:14,331 --> 00:06:15,713
What is it that we actually see?

49
00:06:16,595 --> 00:06:21,221
We know through our psychology tests that we hardly see anything.

50
00:06:21,781 --> 00:06:25,127
Everything that we think we see is manufactured by the mind.

51
00:06:25,567 --> 00:06:34,959
And in a most mysterious way, the mind takes in the information, makes it up, throws it back on the retina to give us the impression that we're actually seeing it.

52
00:06:37,959 --> 00:06:41,843
In terms of the tongue, what is it that the tongue actually experiences?

53
00:06:41,923 --> 00:06:48,411
But very small changes in chemical touchings and pressures and heat.

54
00:06:49,172 --> 00:06:50,973
Very, very, very, very basic.

55
00:06:52,355 --> 00:07:02,406
Now, on that, the mind takes it in and begins to perceive it as a specific feeling.

56
00:07:02,747 --> 00:07:04,930
And that's what the Buddha means by Vedana.

57
00:07:05,855 --> 00:07:13,446
And when that perception is made, there's always a judgment made about it.

58
00:07:13,887 --> 00:07:15,228
And the judgment is very simple.

59
00:07:15,769 --> 00:07:17,271
Pleasant, unpleasant.

60
00:07:18,553 --> 00:07:19,375
Full stop, that's it.

61
00:07:19,896 --> 00:07:28,369
So you get this sensation come in, the mind takes it in, perceives it, and decides pleasant or unpleasant.

62
00:07:29,259 --> 00:07:35,769
There are some pleasant, unpleasant feelings that are so fine that the Buddha then also talks about neutral feelings.

63
00:07:36,309 --> 00:07:43,718
But even when you get close to them, you'll find that they shade off either into pleasant or unpleasant.

64
00:07:43,738 --> 00:07:46,423
So there's your first distinction when it comes to feelings.

65
00:07:47,283 --> 00:07:50,749
Feelings are something manufactured by the mind out of data.

66
00:07:52,911 --> 00:07:54,574
This is coming from the outside world.

67
00:07:55,375 --> 00:07:57,057
It's coming from the outside world to us.

68
00:08:00,783 --> 00:08:08,814
In the same way, when the mind moves in the body, the first thing that we feel are sensations.

69
00:08:10,415 --> 00:08:12,959
The heaviness of depression, the wobbliness of fear.

70
00:08:13,620 --> 00:08:22,452
We can be aware of the sensation, we can be aware of the emotion, but at base it's causing similar sensations on the physical structure.

71
00:08:24,052 --> 00:08:32,260
These are also relayed to the mind and in Buddhist understanding are determined, judged as pleasant or unpleasant.

72
00:08:33,962 --> 00:08:34,964
Now that's Vedana.

73
00:08:35,163 --> 00:08:39,749
And the Vedana is a conditioned thing.

74
00:08:39,769 --> 00:08:42,912
We can't do anything about it.

75
00:08:42,951 --> 00:08:44,452
It's just part of our conditioning.

76
00:08:45,433 --> 00:08:52,221
We're conditioned to experience pleasant or unpleasant things with that little bit in the middle which is neutral.

77
00:08:58,394 --> 00:09:06,486
Now, at that base where it's first of all experienced, the Buddha calls that this contact.

78
00:09:06,966 --> 00:09:17,182
And he says that at that very deep level, that very first level of physical contact, either with mind, where the mind and the body meet.

79
00:09:18,125 --> 00:09:22,831
So when that light comes into the eye, there's that sense base.

80
00:09:23,317 --> 00:09:47,587
and at that point you get a meeting of the physical sensation with consciousness and at that level he says that there are only four distinctive feelings and they're put in a metaphorical way as fire, earth, water and air but they represent heat

81
00:09:48,192 --> 00:10:13,778
hot and cold pressure that's the earth element hardness, softness movement and cohesion elasticity so when you're watching the breath this is of course more obvious if you're watching it down here sometimes you can sense just the movement pure movement as it were and then you can be aware of a sort of elasticity

82
00:10:14,821 --> 00:10:20,048
When you put your foot on the ground and press into it, what you're primarily feeling is that earth pressure.

83
00:10:21,571 --> 00:10:23,472
Heat, of course, is pretty obvious.

84
00:10:26,336 --> 00:10:33,447
Now, from these four basic things, and every sensation, according to the Buddha, has some percentage of each of these.

85
00:10:34,769 --> 00:10:37,452
It's not as though the one appears purely by itself.

86
00:10:37,736 --> 00:10:45,470
Each sensation has some sort of combination, and out of that, the mind has a perception of a feeling.

87
00:10:45,870 --> 00:10:53,484
Of course, this stuff's coming in at pretty fast speed, and the mind sort of gathers it into a percept, a perception.

88
00:10:54,105 --> 00:10:58,091
And from that, it makes this judgment about being pleasant and unpleasant.

89
00:11:03,235 --> 00:11:09,640
Now, the next thing that happens is our reaction to those things.

90
00:11:10,601 --> 00:11:13,104
So here we have the wheel of dependent origination.

91
00:11:13,745 --> 00:11:18,688
We have the contact of the feeling that arises and then we have the reaction.

92
00:11:19,409 --> 00:11:23,813
The reaction, the tanha, is rather unfortunately translated as craving.

93
00:11:24,615 --> 00:11:32,162
But it's a desire for not wanting what is painful and a desire for wanting what is beautiful, what is pleasant.

94
00:11:33,543 --> 00:11:40,812
That is a movement, again, in our psychology, in our mind, of going towards the object in a particular way.

95
00:11:41,614 --> 00:11:47,322
Either to get stuck in it and really enjoy it, or to try and push it away aggressively.

96
00:11:47,863 --> 00:11:49,504
And if that doesn't work, you run for it.

97
00:11:51,107 --> 00:11:52,769
It's a form of aversion.

98
00:11:53,892 --> 00:11:59,919
Now, once that has come up, you see, the next position is a form of identity.

99
00:12:00,139 --> 00:12:01,322
The I comes in.

100
00:12:01,893 --> 00:12:09,322
According to the Buddha, there's no I, there's no sense of me in all that process until that very point.

101
00:12:10,344 --> 00:12:14,028
When the I want comes up, I don't want.

102
00:12:14,048 --> 00:12:22,740
And as soon as there's that association, as soon as there's that identity, very difficult to catch the moment, this wanting and not wanting is empowered.

103
00:12:24,003 --> 00:12:25,163
And that's the act of will.

104
00:12:25,884 --> 00:12:30,110
Will is the power that takes something out of potential into the actual.

105
00:12:30,479 --> 00:12:37,368
So, for instance, in your walking meditation, you can stand there for a year and a day saying intending to walk.

106
00:12:38,589 --> 00:12:39,971
And then something magical happens.

107
00:12:40,110 --> 00:12:41,852
The foot moves.

108
00:12:41,873 --> 00:12:42,774
See if you can catch it.

109
00:12:43,095 --> 00:12:48,701
See if you can find out what's the difference between intending a footstep and the footsteps moving.

110
00:12:48,721 --> 00:13:00,216
And what we catch in that moment is the differentiation between this grasping by the eye, the upadana, to the actual empowerment of it through will, which is the bhava.

111
00:13:00,500 --> 00:13:02,442
Now, Baba translates as becoming.

112
00:13:02,822 --> 00:13:03,585
That's your karma.

113
00:13:06,048 --> 00:13:11,756
Now, the importance of this line is to see exactly where our power actually resides.

114
00:13:12,477 --> 00:13:22,052
Because if we can see that, we can let go of old conditioning and restart new, more skillful one.

115
00:13:22,072 --> 00:13:25,056
Now, that whole business afterwards...

116
00:13:25,778 --> 00:13:34,330
the desire, the craving and all that, is a mental reaction to a given and constitutes the beginning of our emotional life.

117
00:13:34,970 --> 00:13:37,433
These are what's known as the sankara, the conditionings.

118
00:13:39,616 --> 00:13:40,658
That's the mental life.

119
00:13:40,817 --> 00:13:45,024
And this is all our mentation and all our emotions.

120
00:13:45,043 --> 00:13:54,537
So even in the five heaps that the Buddha calls, that he deconstructs the human being into, the five khandhas, first of all there's the body.

121
00:13:55,124 --> 00:13:56,326
Then there's feelings.

122
00:13:56,666 --> 00:13:57,908
Then there's perception.

123
00:13:58,568 --> 00:13:59,951
This whole mentation business.

124
00:14:00,272 --> 00:14:02,716
Then there's the sankara, the conditioning.

125
00:14:03,336 --> 00:14:06,280
And finally, the act of consciousness that knows it.

126
00:14:08,124 --> 00:14:10,727
So he's constantly deconstructing an event.

127
00:14:11,249 --> 00:14:14,653
And the purpose of it is to take this sense of I out of it.

128
00:14:16,697 --> 00:14:20,202
So here we have three distinctions that we feel in our meditation.

129
00:14:21,212 --> 00:14:26,640
We feel at base some sort of basic sensation.

130
00:14:27,361 --> 00:14:35,674
Even now as you're sitting there, like just the pressure of sitting on the floor there, you see, at that base there, you're getting in contact.

131
00:14:35,754 --> 00:14:39,721
If you center in just on those feelings, you're getting in contact with the earth element.

132
00:14:41,163 --> 00:14:46,191
And because it's neither painful nor unpleasant, the mind can ignore it.

133
00:14:46,677 --> 00:14:48,580
So we're hardly aware of those things.

134
00:14:48,740 --> 00:14:51,365
That's our reaction to what we don't really feel.

135
00:14:52,527 --> 00:14:58,998
If the posture then moves into a bit of pain, suddenly, you see, there's pain.

136
00:14:59,057 --> 00:15:01,481
Then you get this reaction, got to move, got to do this, got to do that.

137
00:15:04,005 --> 00:15:06,971
So what we have is this base of sensation.

138
00:15:08,452 --> 00:15:10,677
Then we have a feeling come up.

139
00:15:11,062 --> 00:15:33,964
which is a perception of that as pleasant and unpleasant so now it's as it were clouded with a or should we say surrounded with a mental a mental quality of being pleasant unpleasant and this immediately begins for the mind to start shaking and it shakes in the sense of do i want it or don't want it and that's where we're catching it now

140
00:15:34,635 --> 00:15:39,520
Normally speaking, in our own little deluded ways, we just run the gamut.

141
00:15:40,241 --> 00:15:47,249
And without knowing it, we're just recreating the old sensations, the old pleasures, the old ways of acting.

142
00:15:47,269 --> 00:15:58,681
But in our meditation, what we ought to be doing is putting our mind right there at the feeling and seeing that movement of wanting to indulge, wanting not to indulge.

143
00:16:00,702 --> 00:16:04,407
And what we're catching there is how we create suffering for ourselves.

144
00:16:08,976 --> 00:16:21,611
So if we have those three things quite distinct in our minds, then when we begin to meditate, we can actually go through this stage of actually perceiving the way things really are.

145
00:16:22,793 --> 00:16:24,534
It's an intellectual thing at first.

146
00:16:24,655 --> 00:16:31,744
It's an actual, although we feel these things, although we experience these things, there is a thought process going around it.

147
00:16:31,960 --> 00:16:40,735
Now do remember that that thought process is this very consciousness which is to be enlightened, mirroring back to itself what it's come to experience.

148
00:16:43,019 --> 00:16:47,386
So it's not to be sort of pushed out of the way, but to just be acknowledged.

149
00:16:47,636 --> 00:16:59,991
So, for instance, in the Mahasi technique that I teach, you see, that is actually brought to the fore, where a word actually encapsulates, tries to encapsulate in some way, the experience that's being had.

150
00:17:00,432 --> 00:17:02,554
So it's an acknowledgement of it.

151
00:17:03,056 --> 00:17:05,038
And acknowledge means to know you know.

152
00:17:10,944 --> 00:17:13,407
So, by...

153
00:17:13,809 --> 00:17:27,931
by deconstructing an event, by seeing that there's the primary sensations, there I'm beginning to experience it as pleasant, unpleasant, and here's my relationship to it.

154
00:17:27,951 --> 00:17:31,576
Wanting, not wanting.

155
00:17:31,596 --> 00:17:40,088
Now, when it comes to the discourse on how to establish mindfulness, you can see that the Buddha, he actually wants us to do this.

156
00:17:42,011 --> 00:17:43,294
The first thing he says is,

157
00:17:45,416 --> 00:17:46,178
Meditators.

158
00:17:46,557 --> 00:17:50,821
How does a meditator abide contemplating feelings as feelings?

159
00:17:51,442 --> 00:17:55,727
Now, here, the word he uses is vedana vedanupasiti.

160
00:17:56,708 --> 00:18:03,414
It translates literally as a location to see feelings in feelings, which doesn't particularly make sense in English.

161
00:18:03,855 --> 00:18:07,920
But it's just saying that when you feel a feeling, just feel the feeling.

162
00:18:08,780 --> 00:18:09,701
Don't think about it.

163
00:18:09,761 --> 00:18:11,022
Actually, feel the feeling.

164
00:18:11,063 --> 00:18:15,086
It means that you've got to go into the feeling and feel the feeling.

165
00:18:17,529 --> 00:18:18,530
I'm sure you all know what I mean.

166
00:18:19,413 --> 00:18:22,297
Thank you.

167
00:18:22,317 --> 00:18:30,188
And he says, and here, when a pleasant feeling arises, the meditator understands, I feel a pleasant feeling.

168
00:18:30,868 --> 00:18:36,195
When an unpleasant feeling arises, the meditator understands, I feel an unpleasant feeling.

169
00:18:36,215 --> 00:18:42,645
And when a neither pleasant nor unpleasant feeling arises, the meditator understands, I feel a neither pleasant nor unpleasant feeling.

170
00:18:43,006 --> 00:18:44,347
It's extraordinarily simple.

171
00:18:45,711 --> 00:18:48,836
And you say, oh, that is an unpleasant feeling.

172
00:18:49,958 --> 00:18:52,000
You actually have to make it conscious, you see.

173
00:18:52,421 --> 00:19:02,054
Now, although he's actually putting it in a phrase, I feel an unpleasant feeling, it's simply pointing to a direct experience of it.

174
00:19:02,074 --> 00:19:05,378
Because the word he uses here for to know is paginati.

175
00:19:05,959 --> 00:19:09,284
And paginati is the same word as panya, it's the same word as buddho.

176
00:19:09,664 --> 00:19:15,211
It's intuitive intelligence, a direct perception.

177
00:19:16,406 --> 00:19:22,237
So then he goes on to say, when a pleasant worldly feeling arises, the meditator understands it.

178
00:19:22,277 --> 00:19:24,480
And then he goes through this bit of unpleasant and pleasant.

179
00:19:24,882 --> 00:19:26,965
And when a pleasant unworldly feeling.

180
00:19:27,346 --> 00:19:39,748
So now he's asking us to distinguish those feelings that arise out of the old ways that we are and the new feelings that are arising out of our meditation.

181
00:19:41,247 --> 00:19:56,884
So when, for instance, some of the seven factors of enlightenment arise, such as interest in what we're doing, which is the piti, such as the sense of tranquility, the pasidi, the sense of equanimity, we should recognize that this isn't just an ordinary worldly feeling.

182
00:19:57,144 --> 00:19:58,227
These are spiritual feelings.

183
00:19:58,207 --> 00:20:12,529
These are feelings which are supporting our meditation, which means that they can be, as it were, not, shall we say, too consciously developed, but definitely not pushed away because they're part of the process of enlightenment.

184
00:20:12,910 --> 00:20:15,334
After all, the end product is to be happy.

185
00:20:16,635 --> 00:20:17,237
Don't forget that.

186
00:20:17,998 --> 00:20:20,501
I mean, we want to try and get happy.

187
00:20:22,692 --> 00:20:34,666
And when we find that we're getting happy because we're having wonderful thoughts about cream cakes and sex drugs and rock and roll, then we have to notice how now this happiness is based on.

188
00:20:35,828 --> 00:20:37,471
And we don't indulge those things.

189
00:20:37,490 --> 00:20:38,751
We don't get into those things.

190
00:20:39,292 --> 00:20:41,174
So he's asking us to make that distinction.

191
00:20:42,876 --> 00:20:48,884
Not only pleasant and unpleasant and neutral, but the fact that some feelings of meditation, even negative ones like boredom,

192
00:20:49,809 --> 00:20:56,079
You have to notice this boredom is because I'm doing something wrong in my meditation.

193
00:20:56,601 --> 00:20:58,022
It's coming out of expectancy.

194
00:20:58,503 --> 00:21:01,608
It's coming because I expect something wonderful to happen and it's not happening.

195
00:21:01,628 --> 00:21:02,430
I'm getting really bored.

196
00:21:04,452 --> 00:21:11,344
So by making that distinction you are helping yourself to hone the skills of meditation.

197
00:21:12,184 --> 00:21:15,951
If you don't make these distinctions then it's just you're wandering.

198
00:21:16,531 --> 00:21:17,673
You're just wandering in a wood.

199
00:21:19,560 --> 00:21:24,468
So having made that statement he then goes on to say how to do it.

200
00:21:28,634 --> 00:21:35,044
First of all he says in this way the meditator abides contemplating feelings as feelings.

201
00:21:38,469 --> 00:21:41,473
He abides contemplating feelings internally.

202
00:21:44,878 --> 00:21:48,825
He abides contemplating feelings as feelings externally.

203
00:21:50,881 --> 00:21:53,242
And then both internally and externally.

204
00:21:53,683 --> 00:22:12,502
